	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--DESIGN CREDITS BEGIN HERE-->
<!-- a href=mailto:bamalen@aol.com -->
Germany caught me with my pants down with his opening that saw him rush straight
into Warsaw.  As both Germany and Russia in plain vanilla Diplomacy games,
I have tried opening against the other with very poor results.  I
have totally abandoned such openings and did not expect it.
Other powers usually come in through the back door if Russia or Germany
oppose each other early.  In Crystal Ball, though, such an unusual opening
makes a lot more sense.  Changing
direction in Crystal Ball is like turning an aircraft carrier around -- it
takes a lot of time.  I don't know if I can come back or not, but I'm sending
my Galicia army to Silesia, and just like his Spring 1901 move to Silesia
was unexpected by me, and left Warsaw wide open, I'm thinking my Spring 1902
move there will be unexpected by him.  Turnabout
is fair play, and I'm headed for Munich or Berlin or Kiel.  If this doesn't
work and if Germany presses his advantage (he has Moscow guaranteed -- show me
a non-Crystal Ball game that has Germany owning both Warsaw and Moscow by
1902!) and if he is not opposed by other powers, then I am a goner.
What a game this is going to be...if I live!

	</td>
	</tr>
